<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-6"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-6')">6</a>. As a side note, I love the foam noise padding on the inside of the door. Such a pragmatic solution to a problem. The Foundation is incomprehensibly Byzantine, yes, but it doesn't have to be <em>needlessly</em> so. The facilities and maintenance of large organizations are more often than not run on duct tape and starter fluid, and there's an elegance to that that's not often appreciated.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-7"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-7')">7</a>. Actually, let's talk about why the soundproofing is necessary. As mentioned later in the article, SCP-087 has two different sounds that come from it: the sound of a child crying for help, and an irregular knocking on the inside of its door. Both are fascinating. The child is obviously a lure to drag people deeper into the stairwell. That, the darkness, and the self-luminescent face of 087-1 are all reminiscent of deep-sea anglerfish. There are signs of extreme violence—the smooth gash on the wall, the strange fluid, the giant hole (that doesn't lead to the next floor down, oddly enough), but there's nothing that would necessarily indicate <em>what</em> caused it. Certainly, 087-1 seems to have never initiated or inflicted violence on any of the explorers; it seems almost more like a sentinel than a malicious apparition. Given all this, the presence of a child's voice is completely ambiguous: it could be an actual child (or equivalent) 087-1 is trying (and failing) to shepherd helpers to, or it could be a lure that is or is not connected to 087-1. The knocking is similarly unclear. Is it a malicious or malevolent entity trying to attract others in? Is it a curious child wondering if anyone will play? Without more information it's impossible to say, but the separate sources seem to indicate separate causes.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-8"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-8')">8</a>. This should be in lumens, the SI unit of <em>perceived</em> brightness (adjusted to human dynamic range). Actually, everything relating to the lighting of the stairwell is off by modern clinical standards (see: &quot;seems to be&quot; weasel wording), but the article as a whole is effective enough that I only noticed it while checking details for this article, on what has to be my tenth or so read.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-9"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-9')">9</a>. Setting the article in the near-future allows for large and cataclysmic events to have occurred in the story without resorting to alternate history, and makes the reader sit up and think about the context surrounding the article. Besides—in about twenty years the problem will solve itself.</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-10"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-10')">10</a>. Volcanoes have a much larger role in the as-yet-unwritten 3333 sequel(s).</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-11"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-11')">11</a>. When someone is running in blind panic from a floating face, instructing them to stop will not work. This is a recurring problem with Series I articles (and articles that [intentionally or not] ape the Series I aesthetic), and a pet peeve of mine. It's even worse when interviewing humanoid SCPs.</div>
